Source: SherLIiC: A Typed Event-Focused Lexical Inference Benchmark for Evaluating Natural Language Inference
Definition: Given two sentences, P and Q, determine if sentence Q is the correct premise for hypothesis sentence P. If sentence Q is the premise of sentence P, the answer "yes" else "no". If sentences P and Q use the same verb-pronoun pairs, then the answer should be "no".

Positive Examples.explanation: The sentences location[A] is pointing at region[B] and region[B] is cooperating with location[A] imply the opposite to each other and hence they share no relation.
If a person[B] is blasting  person*politician[A], it implies person[B] is criticizing  person*politician[A]. So it is trur.

Negative Examples.Q: organization[B] is being sued by organization[A]
Negative Examples.explanation: P and Q are the same sentences with the same words, phrased differently, so Q cannot be a premise of P
There is no relation between P and Q, they imply different meanings, so the answer should be no.
